 Interview Question

> You are given an employee DataFrame with the following columns:
>
> `emp_id`, `name`, `department`, `salary`, `city`
>
> Write PySpark code to:
>
> 1. Drop the **city** column.
> 2. Drop both **department** and **salary** columns in a single statement.
> 3. Display the updated DataFrame.

---

# 📊 Input Dataset

| emp_id | name  | department | salary | city      |
| ------ | ----- | ---------- | ------ | --------- |
| 101    | John  | IT         | 60000  | Mumbai    |
| 102    | David | HR         | 45000  | Delhi     |
| 103    | Alice | IT         | 70000  | Pune      |
| 104    | Bob   | Finance    | 55000  | Hyderabad |
| 105    | Sam   | HR         | 48000  | Chennai   |

---

# ✅ Expected Output

### Task 1 – Drop `city`

| emp_id | name  | department | salary |
| ------ | ----- | ---------- | ------ |
| 101    | John  | IT         | 60000  |
| 102    | David | HR         | 45000  |
| 103    | Alice | IT         | 70000  |
| 104    | Bob   | Finance    | 55000  |
| 105    | Sam   | HR         | 48000  |

---

### Task 2 – Drop `department` and `salary`

| emp_id | name  | city      |
| ------ | ----- | --------- |
| 101    | John  | Mumbai    |
| 102    | David | Delhi     |
| 103    | Alice | Pune      |
| 104    | Bob   | Hyderabad |
| 105    | Sam   | Chennai   |

---

# ✅ Solution 1 – Drop One Column

```python
df = df.drop("city")

df.show()
```

---

# ✅ Solution 2 – Drop Multiple Columns

```python
df = df.drop("department", "salary")

df.show()
```

---

# ⭐ Alternative Solution

Using `select()` instead of `drop()`:

```python
df = df.select(
    "emp_id",
    "name",
    "department",
    "salary"
)

df.show()
```

